'''Sahib Singh Verma ''' (15 March 1943 – 30 June 2007){{Citation needed|date=August 2021}} was an Indian politician and the former senior vice-president of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bjp.org/today/offmem.html | title= List of Office Bearers | accessdate= 1 July 2007 |url-status=dead | publisher= BJP |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070408211510/http://www.bjp.org/today/offmem.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate= 8 April 2007}}</ref> He served as [[Chief Minister]] of [[Delhi]] (1996–1998) and was member of [[13th Lok Sabha]], Parliament of India (1999–2004).<ref name=13th>{{cite web |url= http://parliamentofindia.nic.in/ls/lok13/biodata/13DL03.htm |title= Biographical Sketch Member of Parliament 13th Lok Sabha}}</ref> He served as the [[Minister of Labour and Employment (India)|Union Labour Minister of India]].<ref name="Amitav-31955">{{cite news |title=Sahib Singh wanted to visit Serbia to meet fellow Jats |first=Amitav |last=Ranjan |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/31955/ |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=21 September 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>

== Life ==
Sahib Singh Verma was born on 15 March 1943 in [[Mundka]] village of [[Delhi]] to Chaudhary Mir Singh Verma, a zamindar, and Bharpai Devi in a [[Jat]] family.<ref>{{cite news |title=For Sahib Singh Verma's son, campaigning runs in the family |url=https://indianexpress.com/elections/for-sahib-singh-vermas-son-campaigning-runs-in-the-family-5703667/ |accessdate=23 October 2020 |work=The Indian Express |date=1 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=tribuneindia... Editorial |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99oct10/edit.htm |accessdate=23 October 2020 |work=Tribune India |date=10 October 1999}}</ref> He had 2 brothers [[Master Azad Singh|Azad Singh Verma]] and Attar Singh Verma. He was influenced by Arya Samaj from an early age.{{citation needed|date=March 2022}}

Singh had a PhD degree in [[Library Science]], and started work as librarian in [[Shaheed Bhagat Singh College|Bhagat Singh College]], Delhi.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Delhi CM Sahib Singh Verma dies in road accident |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/Content/Jun302007/national2007063010305.asp?section=updatenews |date=30 June 2007 |accessdate=4 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702164015/http://www.deccanherald.com/Content/Jun302007/national2007063010305.asp?section=updatenews <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=2 July 2007}}</ref> He held a master's degree in Arts, ([[Master of Arts|M.A.]]) and also in [[Library Science]] from [[Aligarh Muslim University]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.amu.ac.in/pro.jsp?did=10065&lid=Prominent%20Alumni | title=LIST OF PROMINENT ALUMNI | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810054850/http://www.amu.ac.in/pro.jsp?did=10065&lid=Prominent%20Alumni | archive-date=2017-08-10}}</ref>

He was married to Sahib Kaur and had two sons and three daughters. One of his sons, [[Parvesh Verma]] is serving as Member of [[Delhi Legislative Assembly]] from [[New Delhi Assembly constituency|New Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-02-08 |title=Arvind Kejriwal loses New Delhi, AAP loses Delhi |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/assembly/story/aap-chief-arvind-kejriwal-loses-high-stakes-new-delhi-seat-to-bjps-parvesh-verma-2676751-2025-02-08 |access-date=2025-02-10 |website=India Today |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Bhushan|first=Shashi|date=23 November 2013|title=Mothers campaigning for sons in Delhi assembly election|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-mothers-campaigning-for-sons-in-delhi-assembly-election-1923839|access-date=22 October
